&lt;div id="outline-container-org0e78c72" class="outline-3"&gt;
&lt;h3 id="org0e78c72"&gt;&lt;span class="section-number-3"&gt;2.4&lt;/span&gt; Cita de Knuth&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;div class="outline-text-3" id="text-2-4"&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
Computer manufacturers estimate that over 25 percent of the running
time on their computers is currently being spent on sorting, when all
their customers are taken into account. There are many installations
in which sorting uses over half of the computing time. From these
statistics we may conclude either that &lt;b&gt;(i)&lt;/b&gt; there are many important
applications of sorting, or &lt;b&gt;(ii)&lt;/b&gt; many people sort when they shouldn’t,
or &lt;b&gt;(iii)&lt;/b&gt; inneficient sorting algorithms are in common use. The real
truth probably involves some of the three alternatives.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div id="outline-container-org0a17481" class="outline-2"&gt;
